---
import LocationLayout from '../../layouts/LocationLayout.astro';
import { marsLocations } from '../../data/marsLocations';

const location = marsLocations.find(loc => loc.id === 'hellas-basin');
if (!location) {
  throw new Error('Hellas Basin location not found');
}
---

<LocationLayout title="Hellas Basin - Mars Location" location={location}>
  <!-- Hero Image Section -->
  <div class="mb-8">
    <div
      class="relative h-96 bg-gradient-to-r from-gray-900 to-orange-900 rounded-lg overflow-hidden"
    >
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-black/20"></div>
      <div class="absolute bottom-6 left-6 text-white">
        <p class="text-sm opacity-80">
          MOLA topographic view of Hellas Basin showing its immense depth
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs opacity-60">NASA/MOLA Science Team</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Overview Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Overview</h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Hellas Basin stands as a monument to the violent early history of our
          solar system. With a diameter of 2,300 kilometers and a depth reaching
          9 kilometers below the Martian datum, it is not only the largest
          impact crater on Mars but the largest well-preserved impact structure
          in the entire solar system.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          This colossal basin was carved during the Late Heavy Bombardment
          period, approximately 4.1 to 3.8 billion years ago, when a massive
          asteroid or protoplanet estimated to be around 370 kilometers in
          diameter struck the southern highlands of Mars with devastating force.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Today, Hellas Basin serves as both a geological laboratory and a
          natural atmospheric laboratory, with unique features ranging from
          possible buried glaciers to honeycomb terrain formations that continue
          to puzzle planetary scientists.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Quick Facts Sidebar -->
      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Quick Facts</h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Diameter:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">2,300 km</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Depth:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">9 km below datum</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Age:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">4.1-3.8 billion years</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Impactor Size:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">~370 km diameter</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Atmospheric Pressure:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">1.15 kPa (twice Mars average)</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Formation and Impact Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      The Great Impact
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-red-900/30 to-orange-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-red-700/50"
    >
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        The formation of Hellas Basin represents one of the most catastrophic
        events in Mars' history. The impact that created this massive depression
        released energy equivalent to billions of nuclear weapons, fundamentally
        altering the planet's geology and possibly its early atmosphere.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Impact Mechanics
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Impactor velocity: ~20-25 km/s</li>
            <li>• Energy released: >10²⁶ joules</li>
            <li>• Ejecta thrown across entire planet</li>
            <li>• Created ring mountains up to 2 km high</li>
            <li>• Excavated material to 15+ km depth</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Geological Consequences
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Triggered global hot rainfall</li>
            <li>• Induced massive volcanic activity</li>
            <li>• Created antipodal effects at Alba Patera</li>
            <li>• Altered planetary crustal structure</li>
            <li>• Exposed deep crustal materials</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Unique Features Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Extraordinary Geological Features
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-900/50 to-blue-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-blue-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Honeycomb Terrain</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          One of Mars' most mysterious features, the honeycomb terrain consists
          of flat-lying polygonal "cells" with concentric layers resembling a
          giant honeycomb. These formations may have been created by ice diapirs
          - massive ice bodies pushing up through overlying rock layers.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          The ice layers responsible could have been 100 meters to 1 kilometer
          thick, creating dome structures that were later eroded to reveal the
          current circular patterns.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-cyan-900/50 to-cyan-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-cyan-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Buried Glaciers</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          SHARAD radar data from Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter has detected buried
          ice deposits up to 450 meters thick in eastern Hellas. These "lobate
          debris aprons" are actually glaciers of water ice hidden beneath
          protective layers of dirt and rock.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          The region shows evidence of multiple glaciation periods, suggesting
          complex climate cycles that repeatedly accumulated and melted ice
          deposits over geological time.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
        Twisted "Taffy Pull" Terrain
      </h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        The floor of Hellas Basin displays remarkable twisted bands and viscous
        flow features that resemble taffy being pulled and stretched. These
        formations suggest that the basin floor materials underwent deformation,
        possibly due to ice content or thermal processes.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
        High-resolution HiRISE images reveal intricate patterns of ridges and
        valleys that indicate flow-like behavior of materials across the basin
        floor, creating some of the most alien-looking landscapes on Mars.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Atmospheric Dynamics Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Atmospheric Laboratory
    </h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Hellas Basin's immense depth creates a unique atmospheric environment
          on Mars. At the bottom of the basin, atmospheric pressure reaches 1.15
          kPa - nearly twice the Martian average and remarkably close to the
          triple point of water (0.61 kPa), where liquid water can theoretically
          exist under the right temperature conditions.
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
          <div class="border-l-4 border-orange-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">Dust Storm Genesis</h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              The basin frequently generates localized dust storms that can grow
              into planet-spanning events. The unique topography and atmospheric
              dynamics create ideal conditions for dust lifting and transport.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              Temperature Variations
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              The deep basin experiences more moderate temperature swings than
              the Martian surface average, with the thicker atmosphere providing
              better thermal regulation.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-green-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">Cloud Formation</h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Water ice clouds frequently form in and around the basin,
              particularly during southern winter when atmospheric conditions
              favor condensation.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Pressure Comparison
        </h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Mars Average:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">0.6 kPa</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Hellas Basin:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">1.15 kPa</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Water Triple Point:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">0.61 kPa</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Earth Sea Level:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">101.3 kPa</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Water and Ice History Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Ancient Water and Ice Activity
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-900/30 to-blue-800/20 p-6 rounded-lg border border-blue-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Evidence of Ancient Lakes
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Orbital imagery has revealed what appear to be ancient shorelines,
          delta formations, and terraced deposits within Hellas Basin. These
          features suggest that the basin may have periodically contained large
          bodies of liquid water during Mars' more hospitable past.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          The combination of the basin's depth, which provides higher
          atmospheric pressure, and possible greenhouse warming could have
          created conditions suitable for stable liquid water for extended
          periods.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-cyan-900/30 to-cyan-800/20 p-6 rounded-lg border border-cyan-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Glacial Activity</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Subsurface radar mapping has revealed extensive ice deposits buried
          beneath dust and debris. These buried glaciers represent remnants of
          past ice ages when Mars' axial tilt was different, allowing ice to
          accumulate at lower latitudes.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          The ice deposits show evidence of flow patterns and multiple episodes
          of accumulation and melting, indicating that Hellas Basin has
          experienced repeated cycles of glaciation throughout its history.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Terraforming Potential Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Terraforming Assessment
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-yellow-900/30 to-yellow-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-yellow-700/50"
    >
      <div class="flex items-center mb-6">
        <div
          class="w-12 h-12 bg-yellow-600 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mr-4"
        >
          <span class="text-white font-bold text-xl">6</span>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">
            Moderate Terraforming Potential
          </h3>
          <p class="text-yellow-300">
            Unique advantages offset by significant challenges
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Advantages</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Highest atmospheric pressure on Mars</li>
            <li>• Potential access to buried ice deposits</li>
            <li>• Natural atmospheric containment</li>
            <li>• Large flat areas for development</li>
            <li>• Possible liquid water conditions</li>
            <li>• Rich mineral diversity from impact</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Challenges</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Extreme southern latitude location</li>
            <li>• Severe dust storm activity</li>
            <li>• Limited direct sunlight in winter</li>
            <li>• Complex terrain features</li>
            <li>• Uncertain ice accessibility</li>
            <li>• Potential for toxic perchlorates</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Scientific Exploration Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Scientific Exploration
    </h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Orbital Studies</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Multiple Mars orbiters have studied Hellas Basin extensively, using
          everything from high-resolution cameras to ground-penetrating radar.
          These studies have revealed the basin's complex geological history and
          hidden ice deposits.
        </p>
        <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-300 text-sm">
          <li>• Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter (MRO)</li>
          <li>• Mars Express</li>
          <li>• Mars Global Surveyor</li>
          <li>• Mars Odyssey</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Future Mission Potential
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Hellas Basin represents a prime target for future Mars missions,
          particularly those focused on subsurface exploration and ice
          prospecting. The basin's unique features could provide insights into
          Mars' climate history and potential for past life.
        </p>
        <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-300 text-sm">
          <li>• Ice drilling missions</li>
          <li>• Atmospheric research stations</li>
          <li>• Geological sampling expeditions</li>
          <li>• Climate monitoring networks</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Theoretical Terraforming Concepts Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Theoretical Terraforming Concepts
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-900/30 to-purple-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-purple-700/50"
    >
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Hellas Basin has been the subject of numerous theoretical terraforming
        studies due to its unique atmospheric properties. Some concepts propose
        using the basin as a testing ground for atmospheric manipulation
        technologies or as a contained environment for initial terraforming
        experiments.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Atmospheric Concentration
          </h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-3">
            Theoretical proposals include using the basin's natural depth to
            concentrate denser atmospheres, potentially creating habitable zones
            within the depression while the rest of Mars remains hostile.
          </p>
          <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Dense gas injection experiments</li>
            <li>• Greenhouse gas concentration</li>
            <li>• Partial pressure dome concepts</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Ice Utilization</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-3">
            The buried ice deposits could serve as both a water source and a
            means of atmospheric enhancement through controlled sublimation and
            chemical processing.
          </p>
          <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Large-scale ice extraction</li>
            <li>• Atmospheric water injection</li>
            <li>• Pressure regulation systems</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- External Resources Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Learn More</h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">NASA Resources</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.nasa.gov/news/releases/2008/PIA11433.html"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Buried Glaciers Discovery
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://mars.nasa.gov/mro/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.nasa.gov/offices/mep/overview/index.html"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Mars Exploration Program
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">Research Papers</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hellas_Planitia"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Hellas Planitia Overview
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.whiteclouds.com/articles/hellas-basin/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Geological Analysis
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</LocationLayout>

